# Rebuild Protocol

**A rebuild keeps every feature and rebuilds the app the right way.**

Here's what a rebuild actually is, in plain terms: you built a site, then bolted a feature on, then bolted another feature on top of that, and another. Eventually it works, but it's a stack of cards -- modules layered on modules that don't fit together, things in the wrong place, features that don't play nicely with each other, CSS that doesn't line up, settings scattered around. A rebuild is: *"Now that I know all the features I actually want, let's build it again from scratch -- with all of those features designed in from the start, organized and built correctly."*

So two things are true at once:

1. **Every feature survives.** Nothing the app can do today gets lost. This is non-negotiable (a past rebuild silently dropped ~75% of the UI features -- never again).
2. **The look and structure get FIXED, not copied.** Things that are misplaced get moved to where they belong. Things that should be grouped get grouped. Broken or clashing interactions get fixed. Misaligned CSS gets rebuilt so it lines up and works. The app should come out cleaner, more coherent, and more solid than the pile it replaced.

**Everything is on the table.** Framework, packages, language, hosting, database, build tools -- all of it can change unless the user specifically says to keep something. If a completely different tech stack would be better, propose it.

---

## The #1 Rule: Keep Every Feature. Improve the Structure.

This rule has two halves. The first half is sacred. The second half is the whole point of doing a rebuild.

### Half 1: No feature gets dropped (sacred)

**The old app is the source of truth for WHAT the app can do.** Every capability the user has today must exist in the rebuilt app:

- Every page, every button, every dialog, every form, every import/export action, every settings option, every filter, every bulk action, every row action, every column of data.
- Before rebuilding an area, you MUST read the old code for it so you know every feature it contains. Never work "from memory" or from a loose summary when the actual old code is right there.
- **The "engine vs car" failure:** building all the backend logic and then shipping read-only skeleton pages is a FAILURE, even if the architecture is beautiful. The user cannot use an engine. Every backend capability must be wired to a real, working UI control.
- "It compiles and renders a table" is not done. If the feature existed before, it exists and works after.

**If the old app's source code is available, it must stay accessible for the entire rebuild.** Note its path in REBUILD-PLAN.md and reference it for every feature so nothing slips through the cracks.

### Half 2: The look and structure should get BETTER (the point of the rebuild)

You are NOT making a pixel-perfect photocopy. The old layout is the thing that got messy -- so fix it:

- **Move what's misplaced.** If a feature lives in a weird spot or doesn't belong on a page, put it where it makes sense.
- **Group what belongs together.** Related settings, related actions, related pages -- bring them together instead of scattered.
- **Fix broken and clashing interactions.** Features that were bolted on and don't work well together (or step on each other) get redesigned so they work as one coherent system.
- **Rebuild the CSS properly.** Don't carry over hacky, misaligned styling. Lay it out so it lines up, is consistent, and works across screen sizes.
- **Fix what was never done right.** If something in the old app is broken, half-finished, or obviously wrong, the rebuild is where it gets done correctly (capture these in the inventory, see Phase 1).

The test is NOT "does it look identical to the old app." The test is "does it have every feature, do they all work, and is it organized and built better than before." A rebuilt app that looks the same but is still a stack of cards has failed.

When a layout or grouping change is significant (moving a whole section, merging pages, restructuring navigation), note it in the inventory and plan so there's a record of what changed and why -- and if a change is a judgment call the user might care about, surface it.

